}}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.  P
olynomials:  Intercepts and Sign.  There are several features about th
e graphs of polynomials which are important to track.  These features \+
inform us about the behavior of the function.  Those features include \+
the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-intercepts of the function                   \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "                       Those values \+
where the graph crosses the x-axis.  Those points are solutions of the
 equation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    reg
ions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the
 function are positive" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "              \+
         Those regions where the graph lies above the x-axis.  For a c
ontinuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regions a
re bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    c.    regions (intervals) in the dom
ain of the function where the values of the function are negative" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions whe
re the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in
 particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercep
ts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "  \+
  d.   y-intercept of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 "  \+
                     The value where the graph crosses the y-axis.  Th
e value of the function when x = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "  \+
  e.   end limits" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "                   \+
    For a polynomial, its values will become either arbitrarily large \+
in a positive sense or arbitrarily large in a negative sense as the do
main values tend to infinity.  Graphically, the values on the graph wi
ll growth arbitrarily large positively (go up off the graph) or arbitr
arily large negative (go down off the graph) as the domain values tend
 to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "                      \+
 Similar behavior holds true for approaches to negative infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 150 "For each
 of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Ch
oose a range that will optimally represent the features of the graph. \+
  " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polynomial find each \+
of the above five graphcial characteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   " }{XPPEDIT 
