{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 70 "end limit positive infinity \+
to the left and to the right both going up" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local extrem
e values and monotonicity.  Beyond information of the type gathered ab
ove about intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important infor
mation can be determined from the so called \"critical points\" of a p
olynomial.  The critical points of a polynomial are the intercepts of \+
its derivative.  Since the derivative of a function at a point represe
nts the slope of the tangent line to the graph of the that function at
 the point, then the intercepts of the derivative are places where the
 the tangent lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizontal line
s.  At such places the graph is neither increasing nor decreasing.  El
sewhere the graph must be either increasing or decreasing.  For a poly
nomial, local extreme values (local maximums or local minimums) must o
ccur at the intercepts of the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are \+
important in analyzing the graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points
 of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                     \+
 For a polynomial these are the intercepts of the derivative of the po
lynomial" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum poin
ts of the graph of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
274 "                      These are points (x,y) on the graph of the \+
function for which the y-value is locally the largest value of the fun
ction.  Nearby values on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x
-value of the point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial.
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the
 graph of a function y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "      \+
                These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function fo
r which the y-value is locally the smallest value of the function.  Ne
arby values on the graph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of
 the point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain o
f the function where the values of the function are increasing" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions whe
re the graph rises as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For \+
a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these region
s are bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity.
" }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions (intervals) in \+
the domain of the function where the values of the function are decrea
sing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those reg
ions where the graph falls as the graph is traversed from left to righ
t.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, thes
e regions are bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- in
finity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
275 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the po
lynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally represent the features o
f the graph.  Include the graph of the deriviative of the polynomial o
n the plot.   Plot the function in red and the derviative in green.   \+
" }{TEXT 269 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomial find each of
 the above ten graphcial characteristics (a.  thru j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 
